                                                   Arun Jaitley to look into grievances
            CRICKET BRIEFS                
	 New Delhi: The Virender Sehwag-led players revolt against the Delhi and District Cricket Association (DDCA) could end soon after DDCA president Arun Jaitely promised to address their grievances after he met Sehwag on Monday.         
	Gautam Gambhir and Ishant Sharma re-joined the camp after Jaitelys assurances.         
	Sehwag has been leading the revolt against the DDCA, alleging corruption and nepotism in selection procedure. His charges were backed by the DDCA vice-president and selection committee chairman Chetan Chauhan.         
	Dravid wish         
	 Mumbai: Impressed with the facilities at the DY Patil Stadium in Navi Mumbai, Indian batsman Rahul Dravid said on Monday that he wants to play at least one international tie at the venue before quitting the game. I did not have the opportunity to play here in the IPL last year. But I had heard so much about the facilities here I want to play at least once in an international tie here before I stop playing, he said.         
	Haddin out         
	 Calcutta: Injured Australia wicket-keeper Brad Haddin has been advised to return home before the ODI and Twenty20 series in England. Haddin had fractured a finger on his left hand prior to the third Ashes Test at Edgbaston and could not play in the match but later returned to the team for the fourth and fifth matches of the series. No replacement would be named, a Cricket Australia release said.         
	Condolence         
	 Calcutta: Howrah Union Monday held a condolence meeting of their 22-year-old cricketer Abhishek Saha, who died in a road accident on August 17. He had scored a match-winning 90 for the club when they defeated Kidderpore in the final of the second division knockout tourmament last season. Saha had represented Bengal in under-15 and under-17 tournaments.         
	Streak role         
	 Harare: Former Zimbabwe captain Heath Streak has been appointed bowling coach for the national side. We have been talking to Heath for some time. We have every confidence that his presence in the changing rooms can only be good for the development of our national team, Zimbabwe Cricket managing director Ozias Bvute said.           STAFF REPORTER AMP; AGENCIES                                                                                                                     
